        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to James Crichton-Browne, 8 June [1870]</ref> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 18), CD expressed a desire to receive photographs from Crichton-Browne of ‘general paralysis of the insane’; he repeated the request in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7478.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to James Crichton-Browne, 8 February 1871</ref> (this volume).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 18, enclosure to <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7134.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from James Crichton-Browne, 15 March 1870</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The photographer may have been George Bracey, whose photograph of a patient in the West Riding Asylum was used to illustrate a paper by Crichton-Browne on acute dementia (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1636.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Crichton-Browne 1874</ref>, p. 276).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Euphoria and grandiose ideas are symptoms of ‘general paralysis’, now known as cerebral syphilis (<hi rend="italic">Butterworth’s medical dictionary</hi>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7635.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to James Crichton-Browne, 28 March [1871]</ref>. CD cites Crichton-Browne for this information in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>, p. 311.</note>
